            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            My Catholic Upbringing
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            teresa roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            I was born into the Catholic Church. I was baptized October 23, 1936, when I was one day old in the St. Ignatius Catholic Church in Scranton, Logan, Arkansas, by Rev. Richard Eveld OSB. Sponsors were my grandparents John Layes, Sr. and Julia Henrica Nehus Beshoner. On that day my grandmother Julia Nehus Beshoner planted a red radiance rose bush in the flower bed in honor of my birth, and was there until the house burned down.  <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe width="100%" height="166" scrolling="no" frameborder="no" src="https://w.soundcloud.com/player/?url=https%3A//api.soundcloud.com/tracks/199139611%3Fsecret_token%3Ds-4kv5u&amp;color=d3d3d3&amp;auto_play=false&amp;hide_related=false&amp;show_comments=true&amp;show_user=true&amp;show_reposts=false"></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “I would go to Mass by myself with the children.”
                </span>
            </div>
            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                My life continued to revolve around the Catholic Church. On Sundays, we went to Mass in the morning, In the afternoon we went to benediction. When I was in elementary school, each Friday, we went to Mass, and we would receive Holy Communion, and before Holy Communion, we had to be fasting, so we brought our breakfast with us, and usually it would be a cold fried egg sandwich, and I’ve always loved fried egg sandwiches, because that was kind of a special treat. On holidays, at the church there was always a nativity scene, on the altar where the Virgin Mary was. <br /><br />

                When I was married, I would go to Mass by myself with the children. And one special time, Cyndi decided that she was not happy being there, so she just started screaming. I tried to quiet her down, but she wouldn’t be quieted or consoled, so I would get up with all four girls and walk out, so after that I left them at home during Mass to be babysat, which was only about an hour or so, and they didn’t have to sit through the whole thing and be really quiet. 
            </span>
            
            <!--span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory0-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory0');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory0" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                I didn’t do a lot of temple recommend interviews, because usually those were done after the block on Sunday, and I was involved with the finance clerk doing the tithing, so the other counselor did most of those. But I think I did 90% of the youth interviews, because we did that on mutual night. I can remember going to girls’ camp and pulling the girls aside and interviewing them at girls’ camp for a temple recommend. I loved going to girls’ camp as a priesthood holder. <br /><br />

                Those were things in my life that I found very meaningful and fulfilling.

                </span>
