        <div id="boxmodex2" class="clearfix">
            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            Led Back to the Church by Teresa      
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            bill roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">There was a period in my life, basically when I went in the army, when I became fairly inactive in the Church. Not totally inactive, just semi-active. I was that way off and on until one day I came home from work and there were missionaries sitting in the living room. Teresa accepted the challenge of having them teach the discussions. My jaw hit the floor that she would be willing to that. “What?!” 
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/124071354" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “She said, ‘Yes,’ and my jaw really hit the floor.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                

                After a couple of discussions, they announced that they were going to have a baptism. Was she ready for that? She said, “Yes,” and my jaw really hit the floor. From that point on it has been a case where we work together. She has kept me on the straight and narrow. She was baptized, we were living in Little Rock, and I ended up serving in the branch presidency there. Then, through various moves, I served in a lot of capacities in the Church. <br /><br />

                It was a case where I was disconnected, not completely, but not doing everything I should be doing, and doing a lot of things I shouldn’t be doing. It helped to have my wife with me. 


            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                I look at myself: I married a woman who was not a member of the Church. My cousin married a woman who was not a member of the Church. My wife is now a strong, dedicated, hard-working member of the Church, and my cousin’s wife is anti-Mormon and always has been. He’s been inactive since the time he was nineteen years old.  <br /><br />

                I see the two different sides of the same equation. I was lucky. My wife became what I needed to have. Otherwise, who knows where I’d be today. So, if you’re going to get married, the secret is, pick the right woman! Or pick the right guy!
                </span>
            </div>

