            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
               When we were first dating, we had a conversation about religion. He told me that he was Mormon. But I didn’t understand that word, “Mormon,” because I’d never really heard it that much, and I thought he said he was a “moron.” To me, I thought it was natural to laugh. “You say you’re a moron? Are you joking, or what?” But he didn’t take it that way. He thought I was being critical of the Church. I was not being critical of the Mormon Church. I was just laughing because I thought he was telling another joke, that he was a moron!
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/124071540" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “‘You say you’re a moron? Are you joking, or what?’”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                

                Time went on; we were married and had children, and we moved to Little Rock, Arkansas. We rented a house, and the landlord of that house didn’t really want to know anything about the Mormon Church, so when the missionaries stopped by his house—on our application we had written down that Bill was a Mormon—so he said, “I have just rented a house to someone who is a Mormon.”<br /><br />

                The missionaries decided they would come over to our house and visit. They came over when Bill was at work, and I asked them to come in, ’cause we were brand new there, I didn’t know anybody, and I thought I would be polite and talk to them. Before that, when the missionaries came, I wasn’t too polite or talked to them because I didn’t want anything to do with the Mormon Church. 


            </span>


            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstorya-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstorya');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstorya" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    They talked and they must have said just the right things, because it made me think about some of the things I had read in different books that were at our house, like <span class="italica">The Way to Perfection,</span> and a few other books. I had not read the Book of Mormon. I probably hadn’t read any of <span class="italica">The Book of Mormon,</span> but I read other information and other leaflets. <br /><br />

                    We went to church that Sunday, and the investigator’s class was with Carroll Dortch. He was also a convert to the Church, and his wife was a convert. He was able to explain a lot of things to me that I didn’t understand. I guess I should say I had previously been to an investigators' class in Minneapolis, and the teacher there was on a lesson that was very controversial to me, and I didn’t accept anything that he taught. It was just too controversial for me. I didn’t believe anything he said.<br /><br />

                    It was Carroll Dortch who was able to know and understand what I needed to know. It was probably things that maybe he needed to know before he was baptized. 
