            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
        
            We got in the car with our four girls and camped all the way out to Idaho. We met at my sister-in-law’s house in Meridian, Idaho, and we met my brother-in-law and his wife there and their two daughters. So we all gathered together at Meridian. The next morning we got up in the middle of the night and drove over to Idaho Falls, which was the closest temple to Meridian at that time. <br /><br />

            My two nieces, who were already born in the covenant, needed a place to stay, so my sister-in-law Marilyn had a friend who lived in Idaho Falls. They were able to stay with friends while the rest of us went to the temple. 

            
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstoryq-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstoryq');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstoryq" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                    Our four girls could go to the temple because they were being sealed. They went to the little nursery where they were dressed in white while we were going to receive our endowments, our initiatories and our endowment. Then we went to the sealing room. The helper in the nursery brought the four little girls in, and they were beautiful, and they were just smiling and happy. We all surrounded the altar as the officiator performed the sealing ordinance. Everybody cried. One of my brother-in-laws gave me a handkerchief, and it was soaking wet with tears.<br /><br />

                    Being sealed in the temple was a very important day for us. We had waited for a long time to be sealed together and to have our children sealed to us. It was also important because we got together with family, with brothers and sisters and nephews and nieces. <br /><br />

                    When we went back to Meridian after the sealing, Marilyn, my sister-in-law, and her husband packed up everything and moved down to Utah. We—Bill and I and our children, and Dan and Lois and their children—drove down to Afton, Wyoming to visit with the Taysom family, their grandfather and grandmother. We were able to visit with them and see their gardens.<br /><br />

                    Then we went to a campground where we spent the night. As we were unpacking our things, along came Bill’s uncle, and he had a big catch of fish. He’d been out fishing that day and knew that we were there, so he brought us a bunch of fish. We had them for dinner. The next morning we had more fish for breakfast! We still had fish left over, so we gave them to another family who were camping in the same campground, and they were delighted to have some fresh fish.<br /><br />

                    After that we drove down to Utah, where Marilyn and her family were, and helped them unload their truck into their new home and spent some time with them. <br /><br />

                    We were able to go to the Salt Lake Temple and go through a session. That was probably the last time we were able to go to the temple for a long, long, long time, because we lived far from the temple. When we would go to visit family, there wasn’t time to go to the temple. We didn’t have babysitters if we did go, so we didn’t go to the temple again until we were in California. In Dublin, California we went to the Oakland Temple.<br /><br />

                    The temple has always been really important to our family.
